SIMPLE: plain
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Plain
<hw>Plain</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>playne</ets>, <ets>pleyne</ets>, fr. F. <ets>plaindre</ets>. See
<er>Plaint</er>.]</ety> <def>To lament; to bewail; to complain.</def>
<mark>[Archaic & Poetic]</mark> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We with piteous heart unto you <qex>pleyne</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plain</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Plain
<hw>Plain</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To lament; to mourn over; <as>as,
to <ex>plain</ex> a loss</as>.</def> <mark>[Archaic & Poetic]</mark>
<rj><au>Sir J. Harrington.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plain</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Plain
<hw>Plain</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Plainer</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Plainest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[F., level, flat, fr. L.
<ets>planus</ets>, perhaps akin to E. <ets>floor</ets>. Cf.
<er>Llano</er>, <er>Piano</er>, <er>Plan</er>, <er>Plane</er> level, a
level surface.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Without elevations or
depressions; flat; level; smooth; even. See <er>Plane</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The crooked shall be made straight, and the rough places
<qex>plain</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Isa. xl. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Open; clear; unencumbered; equal; fair.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our troops beat an army in <qex>plain</qex> fight.</q>
<rj><qau>Felton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Not intricate or difficult; evident; manifest;
obvious; clear; unmistakable.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧'T is a <xex>plain</xex>
case.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Void of extraneous beauty or ornament;
without conspicuous embellishment; not rich; simple.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>Not highly cultivated; unsophisticated; free from show or
pretension; simple; natural; homely; common.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Plain</xex> yet pious Christians.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Hammond.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>plain</xex> people.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>A. Lincoln.</au>
<sd>(c)</sd> <def>Free from affectation or disguise; candid; sincere;
artless; honest; frank.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧An honest mind, and
<xex>plain</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>Not luxurious;
not highly seasoned; simple; <as>as, <ex>plain</ex> food</as>.</def>
<sd>(e)</sd> <def>Without beauty; not handsome; homely; <as>as, a
<ex>plain</ex> woman</as>.</def> <sd>(f)</sd> <def>Not variegated, dyed,
or figured; <as>as, <ex>plain</ex> muslin</as>.</def> <sd>(g)</sd>
<def>Not much varied by modulations; <as>as, a <ex>plain</ex>
tune</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Plain battle</b></col>, <cd>open battle; pitched
battle.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Chaucer.</au> -- <col><b>Plain
chant</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <cd>Same as <cref>Plain song</cref>,
below.</cd> -- <col><b>Plain chart</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a
chart laid down on Mercator's projection.</cd> -- <col><b>Plain
dealer</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>One who practices plain dealing</cd>.
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A simpleton</cd>. <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Shak.</au> --
<col><b>Plain dealing</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Dealing</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Plain molding</b></col> <fld>(Join.)</fld>, <cd>molding of which
the surfaces are plain figures.</cd> -- <col><b>Plain sewing</b></col>,
<cd>sewing of seams by simple and common stitches, in distinct from
fancy work, embroidery, etc.; -- distinguished also from designing and
fitting garments.</cd> -- <col><b>Plain song</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>The Gregorian chant, or <altname>canto fermo</altname>; the
prescribed melody of the Roman Catholic service, sung in unison, in
tones of equal length, and rarely extending beyond the compass of an
octave</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A simple melody.</cd> -- <col><b>Plain
speaking</b></col>, <cd>plainness or bluntness of speech.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Level; flat; smooth; open; artless; unaffected;
undisguised; frank; sincere; honest; candid; ingenuous; unembellished;
downright; blunt; clear; simple; distinct; manifest; obvious; apparent.
See <er>Manifest</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plain</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Plain
<hw>Plain</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a plain manner; plainly.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧To speak short and <xex>pleyn</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Chaucer.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧To tell you <xex>plain</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plain</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Plain
<hw>Plain</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>plaigne</ets>, F.
<ets>plaine</ets>. See <er>Plain</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Level land; usually, an open field or a broad stretch of land with
an even surface, or a surface little varied by inequalities; <as>as, the
<ex>plain</ex> of Jordan; the American <ex>plains</ex>, or
prairies.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Descending fro the mountain into <qex>playn</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Him the Ammonite⟦br⟧
Worshiped in Rabba and her watery <qex>plain</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A field of battle.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lead forth my soldiers to the <qex>plain</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plain</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Plain
<hw>Plain</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Plained</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Plaining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. <er>Plane</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To plane or level; to make plain
or even on the surface.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We would rake Europe rather, <qex>plain</qex> the East.</q>
<rj><qau>Wither.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make plain or manifest; to explain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What's dumb in show, I'll <qex>plain</qex> in speech.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plainant</ent>⟦br⟧
